"Supraglottic airway","Vocal cords","Subglottic region","Trachea","Nasopharynx"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of predominantly expiratory stridor suggests obstruction in the \u003Cstrong\u003Etrachea\u003C/strong\u003E. During expiration, increased intrathoracic pressure causes further narrowing of an already compromised airway, producing the characteristic sound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupraglottic airway\u003C/strong\u003E obstruction causes inspiratory stridor as the tissues collapse inward during inspiration. Obstruction at the \u003Cstrong\u003Evocal cords\u003C/strong\u003E typically produces biphasic stridor (heard during both inspiration and expiration). \u003Cstrong\u003ESubglottic region\u003C/strong\u003E pathology usually causes biphasic stridor with a predominant inspiratory component. \u003Cstrong\u003ENasopharynx\u003C/strong\u003E obstruction typically produces stertor (snoring sounds) rather than stridor. Generally, the lower the anatomical site of obstruction in the airway, the more likely stridor will be predominantly expiratory.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Expiratory stridor is typically caused by lower airway obstruction, particularly in the trachea","Inspiratory stridor is typically caused by upper airway obstruction above or at the vocal cords","The timing of stridor (inspiratory, expiratory, or biphasic) helps localise the anatomical site of obstruction"],"references":["Pfleger A, Eber E. Assessment and causes of stridor. Paediatr Respir Rev. 2016 Mar;18:64-72. doi: 10.1016/j.prrv.2015.10.003. Epub 2015 Oct 23. PMID: 26707546.","Mason, R. J., Broaddus, V. C., Martin, T. R., King, T. E., Schraufnagel, D., Murray, J. F., \u0026 Nadel, J. A. (2010). Murray and Nadel\u0027s textbook of respiratory medicine E-book: 2-volume set. Elsevier Health Sciences.","O Cathain E, Gaffey MM. Upper Airway Obstruction. [Updated 2022 Oct 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK564399/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96227"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15462"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96227"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T13:55:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T13:55:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8153"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114227"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50